-%C - RP1 MSIX configuration utility
-
-Syntax:
-%C [options]
-
-Options:
-   -i: setup rpi IRQs to use, separated by ','
-   -v: set verbosity level
-
-Example - setup MSIX for ethernet (irq 6), USB 2.0 (irq 31), 3.0 (irq 36):
-   %C -i 6,31,36
+%C - RP1 MSIX configuration utility
+
+Syntax:
+%C [-m <mode>] [--mode=<mode>] [-v] [irq_list]
+
+irq_list
+Can specify multiple command separated IRQs and, optionally, whether they are
+edge or level triggered. Each IRQ in irq_list is either a single IRQ or a
+range of IRQs.
+
+irq_list := irq_set | irq_set,irq_set
+irq_set := irq | irq-irq
+irq := <digits> | <digits>irq_cfg
+irq_cfg := disable_flag rp1_flag | rp1_flag
+rp1_flag := level_or_edge | level_or_edge gic_flag
+gic_flag := level_or_edge | level_or_edge mip_flag
+mip_flag := level_or_edge
+disable_flag := D
+level_or_edge := l | e
+
+For the specific flags:
+D == Disable the IRQ. Level/edge configuration is still applied but the IRQ
+     will not be disabled/masked. The default behaviour, when this flag is
+     absent is to enable/unmask the IRQ.
+l == Level triggered.
+e == Edge triggered.
+
+If a level_or_edge flag is not specified the default depends on the specific
+HW unit:
+- rp1_flag has a default of 'l' (level)
+- gic_flag has a default of 'e' (edge)
+- mip_flag has a default of 'e' (edge)
+
+Operating modes:
+%C can operate in different modes. Whatever mode is last specific on the
+command will be the mode of operation. The supported modes and their effects
+are as follows.
+
+status | print | list
+    Prints the IRQ configuration, then exits. This is the default mode.
+
+    By default it will print the information for ALL IRQs unless a specific
+    set of IRQs are requested via an [irq_list].
+
+    Please see above for the form of [irq_list]. Any irq_cfg values are
+    ignored.
+
+    A new instance will fail to run in status mode if there is not another
+    instance running in server mode.
+
+server
+    Exactly one instance of msix-rp1 must be running in server mode to enable
+    the operation of other modes. This mode configures and enables the PCI MSIX
+    link between AP and RP1. Normally the first instance of msix-rp1 started
+    after the system boots is run as a server.
+
+    As a convenience, if any IRQ configurations are specified this mode
+    will configure those IRQs as if the instance was run in 'config' mode.
+    Please see below for the form of [irq_list].
+
+    A new instance will fail to run in server mode if there is already an
+    server instance.
+
+cleanup
+    This mode disables the PCI MSIX link between AP and RP1. It can be used
+    to reset the link into a known good state. Because it will impact and
+    already running server instance, this mode will refuse to operate if
+    there is already a server instance running.
+
+config | set
+    Sets the configuration for the specified IRQs, then exits.
+
+    Please see above for the form of [irq_list].
+
+    A new instance will fail to run in config mode if there is not another
+    instance running in server mode.
+
+
+Options:
+   -m/--mode <mode>     Sets the operating mode for msix-rp1. Valid values are:
+                        server, config, set, status, print, list, and cleanup
+                        Default value is 'status'
+   -v                   Increase verbosity level.
+                        May be specified multiple times
+
+Examples
+  Start a server instance
+    msix-rp1 --mode=server
+
+  Configure MSIX for ethernet (irq 6), USB 2.0 (irq 31), and USB 3.0 (irq 36).
+  Ethernet gets the defaults of level triggered at RP1, and edge triggered
+  at GIC and MIP. The two USB interrupts are explicitly set to be edge
+  triggered at RP1, and the default edge trigger at RP1 and MIP.
+    msix-rp1 --mode=set 6,31e,36e
+
+  As the last example but also configure the three GPIO banks (IRQs 0, 1, and 2)
+  to be level triggered at RP1.
+    msix-rp1 --mode=set 6,31e,36e 0-2
+    or
+    msix-rp1 --mode=set 6,31e,36e,0-2
+    or
+    msix-rp1 --mode=set 6,31e,36e,0,1,2
+
+  Configure I2C1 (irq 8) to be level triggered at all three of RP1, GIC, and MIP.
+  The configuration for other interrupts will be unchanged.
+    msix-rp1 --mode=set 8lll
+
+  Start a server instance that also configures the ethernet (irq 6), USB 2.0
+  (irq 31), and USB 3.0 (irq36) interrupts.
+    msix-rp1 --mode=server 6,31e,36e
+
+  Print the status of all interrupts
+    msix-rp1
+
+  Print the status of just the three GPIO banks
+    msix-rp1 0-2
+    or
+    msix-rp1 0,1,2
+    or
+    msix-rp1 0 1 2
+
